
<p class = 'definition'>
    The <strong>Work-Energy Theorem</strong>
    states that the total work done on a system
    is equal to the change in mechanical energy
    of that system.
</p>

<p>
    In this pod, we will <emph>qualitatively</emph> examine the work-energy theorem.
    In particular, we will look at very simple situations,
    but look at it from the point of view of different systems.
    Our <strong>goal</strong> is to show that, no matter what system
    we chose to focus on,
    the work-energy theorem is <emph>always</emph> followed.
</p>

<p>
    Warning, this is a very <a href = 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pedant'>pedantic</a> topic.
    It is, admittedly, not very fun to learn,
    but is nonetheless crucial to understanding how a <emph>system</emph>
    works.
    (If you are in AP Physics 1, the College Board <emph>loves</emph> these
    kinds of questions!)
</p>


<h4>
    Some Key Principles:
</h4>

<h5>
    Internal and External Forces:
</h5>
<ul class="principleList">
    <li>
        An <strong>internal force</strong> is when something
        inside a system exerts a force on something else
        also inside the system.
        Internal forces CANNOT do work on a system
        and DO NOT appear on a free-body diagram.
    </li>
    <li>
        An <strong>external force</strong> is when something
        outside the system exerts a force on something
        inside the system.
        External forces CAN do work on a system
        and DO appear no a free-body diagram.
    </li>
</ul>
<h5>
    Types of Mechanical Energy
</h5>
<ul class="principleList">
    <li>
        An object alone can have only one type of energy,
        <strong>kinetic energy</strong>.
        If only one object is in a system, it can have
        only kinetic energy.
    </li>
    <li>
        Only two objects that are gravitationally attracted
        can have <strong>gravitational potential energy</strong>.
        Usually, gravitational potential energy exists in a system
        between some object and the earth.
    </li>
</ul>

