        <div class = 'col-6 border border-dark'>
            The ball can have <strong>kinetic energy</strong>.
            It cannot have gravitational potential energy
            because gravity is an interaction between two objects.
        </div>
        <div class = 'col-6 border border-dark'>
            The ball-earth system can have <strong>kinetic energy</strong>
            and <strong>gravitational potential energy</strong>.
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class = 'row'>
        <div class = 'col-12 text-center border border-dark'>
            Does the mechanical energy of the system
            increase, decrease, or stay the same?
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class = 'row'>
        <div class = 'col-6 border border-dark'>
            The ball moves faster as it falls down, gaining kinetic energy,
            so its mechanical energy <strong>increases</strong>.
        </div>
        <div class = 'col-6 border border-dark'>
            In the ball-earth system,
            gravitational potential energy is converted to kinetic energy,
            and the total mechanical energy <strong>stays the same</strong>.
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class = 'row'>
        <div class = 'col-12 text-center border border-dark'>
            Does the system follow the Work-Energy Theorem?
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class = 'row'>
        <div class = 'col-6 border border-dark'>
            <strong>YES</strong>:
            Positive work is done on the system,
            and the system gains mechanical energy.
        </div>
        <div class = 'col-6 border border-dark'>
            <strong>YES</strong>:
            Zero work is done on the system,
            and the total mechanical energy remains the same.
        </div>
    </div>

</div>

