<h4>
    Example 3: Lifting a Book with a Constant Velocity
</h4>

<p>
    Consider a person lifting a book with a constant velocity.
    We are going to consider the situation
    from two different points of view:
    the book system and the book-earth system.
</p>


<div class = 'container'>
    <div class = 'row pt-4 '>
        <div class = 'col-6 border border-dark'>
            The Book System
        </div>
        <div class = 'col-6 border border-dark'>
            The Book-Earth System
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class = 'row'>
        <div class = 'col-12 text-center border border-dark'>
            What external forces act on the system?
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class = 'row'>
        <div class = 'col-6 border border-dark' id = 'book-system-fbd'>
            Two forces act on the book:
            gravity pulling the book downward,
            and the applied force of the person lifting the book upward.
            <br>
        </div>
        <div class = 'col-6 border border-dark' id = 'book-earth-system-fbd'>
            The only external force acting on the book-earth system is the applied force.
            Gravity is an internal force, but because the person lifting the book
            is <emph>not</emph> part of the system, the applied force is an external force.
            <br>
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class = 'row'>
        <div class = 'col-12 text-center border border-dark'>
            Positive, negative, or zero work?
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class = 'row'>
        <div class = 'col-6 text-center border border-dark'>
            Because the book is moving at a constant velocity,
            we know that the net force acting on the book is zero,
            and so <strong>zero work</strong> is done on the book.
        </div>
        <div class = 'col-6 text-center border border-dark'>
            The book is moving upward, and there is an upward
            net force acting on it, so <strong>positive</strong>
            work is done on the book-earth system.
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class = 'row'>
        <div class = 'col-12 text-center border border-dark'>
            What types of mechanical energy does the system have?
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class = 'row'>
        <div class = 'col-6 border border-dark'>
            The book has only <strong>kinetic energy</strong>.
        </div>
        <div class = 'col-6 border border-dark'>
            The book-earth system has both <strong>kinetic energy</strong>
            and <strong>gravitational potential energy</strong>.
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class = 'row'>
        <div class = 'col-12 text-center border border-dark'>
            Does the mechanical energy of the system
            increase, decrease, or stay the same?
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class = 'row'>
        <div class = 'col-6 border border-dark'>
            The book is moving at a constant velocity,
            so it does not gain or lose kinetic energy.
            The total mechanical energy of the system <strong>stays the same</strong>.
        </div>
        <div class = 'col-6 border border-dark'>
            Because the book is gaining height,
            the system gains gravitational potential energy.
            The total mechanical energy of the system <strong>increases</strong>.
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class = 'row'>
        <div class = 'col-12 text-center border border-dark'>
            Does the system follow the Work-Energy Theorem?
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class = 'row'>
        <div class = 'col-6 border border-dark'>
            <strong>YES</strong>:
            Zero work is done on the book, and the books
            mechanical energy stays the same.
        </div>
        <div class = 'col-6 border border-dark'>
            <strong>YES</strong>:
            Positive work is done on the book-earth system,
            and the system gains mechanical energy.
        </div>
    </div>
</div>

